239
00:15:28,693 --> 00:15:30,987
(man speaking German)

240
00:15:31,070 --> 00:15:32,572
Mmm.

241
00:15:34,657 --> 00:15:36,659
(German)

242
00:16:26,334 --> 00:16:28,002
it's Rosa.

243
00:16:30,463 --> 00:16:32,507
Am I bothering you?

244
00:16:32,590 --> 00:16:35,093
I just wanted t-to tell you -

245
00:16:36,469 --> 00:16:38,179
to thank you.

246
00:16:38,262 --> 00:16:39,889
It's good that you're there.

247
00:16:39,972 --> 00:16:41,474
It's good...

248
00:16:42,350 --> 00:16:44,852
that you're accepting the prize.

249
00:16:44,936 --> 00:16:47,063
It's what Wilhelm wanted.

250
00:16:49,816 --> 00:16:51,859
(laughing)
Henryk? No.

251
00:16:51,943 --> 00:16:55,613
You know what he thought of Henryk.

252
00:16:56,864 --> 00:17:01,369
The less he understands, the better he is,
and when he understands nothing he's excellent.

253
00:17:04,539 --> 00:17:08,000
(sighs) I would like to have
given you a hug, but...

254
00:17:08,793 --> 00:17:10,420
but I'm leaving.

255
00:17:11,212 --> 00:17:14,048
I can't stand being alone at Sils.

256
00:17:14,132 --> 00:17:15,842
It's too difficult.

257
00:17:16,509 --> 00:17:19,887
But there's something I want you,

258
00:17:19,971 --> 00:17:22,682
and only you...

259
00:17:29,480 --> 00:17:31,649
(sobs)
to know.

260
00:17:31,733 --> 00:17:35,403
(chattering, laughing, faint)

261
00:17:35,486 --> 00:17:37,572
Mmm.

262
00:17:37,655 --> 00:17:40,408
(laughing, chattering continue)

263
00:17:42,410 --> 00:17:45,371
So he knew about the illness
for a long time?

264
00:17:49,625 --> 00:17:52,628
Did the autopsy say
what he swallowed?

265
00:17:55,465 --> 00:17:57,467
Oh, I see.

266
00:17:58,259 --> 00:18:00,261
He left nothing to chance.

267
00:18:01,345 --> 00:18:03,055
- Beautiful.
-(shutter clicking)

268
00:18:03,139 --> 00:18:04,849
Turn your body a bit sideways, please.

269
00:18:04,932 --> 00:18:07,643
Yeah. And chin up
a little bit, please. Thank you.

270
00:18:07,727 --> 00:18:09,604
Great. Yeah.

271
00:18:09,687 --> 00:18:11,272
- Maria?
- Hmm?

272
00:18:11,355 --> 00:18:15,610
- Sorry. it's, uh, your future ex.
- And again. All right?

273
00:18:15,693 --> 00:18:17,445
- Hold on a second.
- Right, right.

274
00:18:17,528 --> 00:18:19,405
Hello? Allô"?

275
00:18:21,199 --> 00:18:24,994
(in French) Spare me the gloom.
I'm not the one who died.

276
00:18:25,870 --> 00:18:29,874
I know Wilhelm died.
I happen to be in Zurich.

277
00:18:43,054 --> 00:18:44,806
PHOTOGRAPHERS (shouting):
Maria! Maria!

278
00:18:44,889 --> 00:18:46,974
-(man shouts in French)
- Maria!

279
00:18:49,227 --> 00:18:51,562
- Maria!
- Maria!

280
00:18:51,646 --> 00:18:53,147
The press is all here.

281
00:18:53,231 --> 00:18:56,234
I don't know how
we'll squeeze them all in.

282
00:18:57,443 --> 00:19:01,322
MAN: One thing you should know -
we met very early, at the university.

283
00:19:01,405 --> 00:19:03,741
We were both studying
literature and theology.

284
00:19:06,577 --> 00:19:10,540
And I had the privilege of acting
in all of his plays, here and abroad.

285
00:19:10,623 --> 00:19:13,960
He had become a recluse -
mysterious, inaccessible.

286
00:19:14,043 --> 00:19:16,629
Wilhelm was the simplest man
in the world.

287
00:19:17,463 --> 00:19:21,300
He liked to ski in the winter
and go hiking in the summer.

288
00:19:21,384 --> 00:19:23,845
Those are the fondest memories
I have of him.

289
00:19:23,928 --> 00:19:27,473
His later work depicts
a bleak, destructive vision.

290
00:19:27,557 --> 00:19:29,600
I acted in those plays.

291
00:19:31,060 --> 00:19:32,436
Mmm, it's true.

292
00:19:32,520 --> 00:19:35,523
At times I found them scary.

293
00:19:38,985 --> 00:19:41,737
A sea of gray hair.

294
00:19:43,990 --> 00:19:45,491
Completely.

295
00:19:46,617 --> 00:19:49,620
So, first I'll say a few words.

296
00:19:49,704 --> 00:19:52,206
(chuckling)
I hope I am up to the task.

297
00:19:52,290 --> 00:19:53,916
And then I'll introduce Henryk.

298
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:57,712
Once he has finished,
he asks you to join him on stage.

299
00:19:57,795 --> 00:20:00,256
You'll introduce the film.
That's it.

300
00:20:15,396 --> 00:20:17,648
I saw Wilhelm two weeks ago.

301
00:20:19,650 --> 00:20:21,152
We went hunting.

302
00:20:22,862 --> 00:20:26,449
He was his usual self.
There and not there.

303
00:20:29,785 --> 00:20:32,788
He mentioned the prize,
said he wouldn't be attending.

304
00:20:34,332 --> 00:20:36,584
I told him he'd miss
an opportunity to see you.

305
00:20:36,667 --> 00:20:41,130
I was on Long Island six months ago.
I spent a week with him and Rosa.

306
00:20:41,213 --> 00:20:43,382
- I know.
- I don't give a fuck that you know.

307
00:20:43,466 --> 00:20:45,009
(door opens)

308
00:20:45,092 --> 00:20:47,595
Henryk, you are almost on.

309
00:20:47,678 --> 00:20:49,847
-(speaks German)
- Excuse me.

310
00:20:50,598 --> 00:20:52,808
(Urs speaking German)

311
00:20:55,102 --> 00:20:58,272
We had an affair when we
were shooting Maloja <i>Snake.</i>

312
00:20:58,356 --> 00:21:01,609
- Yeah, I couldn't tell.
- I was 18, kind of dumb.

313
00:21:01,692 --> 00:21:03,694
And he really took advantage.

314
00:21:04,695 --> 00:21:07,156
After the shoot,
I never heard from him.

315
00:21:07,239 --> 00:21:10,159
- It destroyed me.
- I'm sure you've run into him since.

316
00:21:11,410 --> 00:21:13,704
We made another film together
afterwards.

317
00:21:14,914 --> 00:21:17,291
- Which one?
- Oh, you don't want to know.

318
00:21:17,375 --> 00:21:20,086
Tolstoy adaptation.
German producers.

319
00:21:20,169 --> 00:21:22,838
(laughs) Who cares, huh?

320
00:21:22,922 --> 00:21:25,007
Well, 10 years later, I was famous.

321
00:21:25,091 --> 00:21:27,468
<i>Then</i> he was interested.

322
00:21:27,551 --> 00:21:30,596
And he kept harassing me,
calling me in the middle of the night.

323
00:21:30,680 --> 00:21:33,516
But I didn't give in, and that he hated.

324
00:21:33,599 --> 00:21:37,895
And he made me pay for it
every single day of the shooting.

325
00:21:37,979 --> 00:21:42,566
He was really amazing in that one movie -
Um, what is it called?

326
00:21:43,359 --> 00:21:47,446
He plays a Soviet defector
with, like, missile codes and shit.

327
00:21:47,530 --> 00:21:49,824
- Um, do you know?
- No, I don't know.

328
00:21:49,907 --> 00:21:52,201
Never heard of it.

329
00:21:52,284 --> 00:21:54,578
He's great in it.

330
00:21:54,662 --> 00:21:57,289
So intense, especially
in the more physical scenes.

331
00:21:57,373 --> 00:22:00,167
That stare. He is like...

332
00:22:00,251 --> 00:22:02,837
- I like him.
- Yeah, I kind of got it.

333
00:22:02,920 --> 00:22:06,048
I mean, as an actor
I really like him. I -

334
00:22:09,343 --> 00:22:12,096
(Speaking German)

335
00:22:13,180 --> 00:22:17,852
<i>(in German) Unfortunately,
he must leave tomorrow morning.</i>

336
00:22:17,935 --> 00:22:20,021
<i>Henryk Wald!</i>

337
00:22:24,275 --> 00:22:29,905
<i>(m Germany.
I stood on this stage four years ago</i>

338
00:22:29,989 --> 00:22:32,658
<i>in</i> the <i>play</i> The Reichstag is Burning

339
00:22:32,742 --> 00:22:34,285
<i>by Wilhelm Melchior.</i>

340
00:22:35,953 --> 00:22:40,124
<i>Little did I know
it would be Wilhelm's last play.</i>

341
00:22:40,207 --> 00:22:42,793
<i>He was sitting there in the third row,</i>

342
00:22:42,877 --> 00:22:44,795
<i>staring at me.</i>

343
00:22:46,047 --> 00:22:48,215
<i>My acting was never so lousy.</i>

344
00:22:49,091 --> 00:22:51,135
Maria, you're on in five minutes.

345
00:22:51,218 --> 00:22:53,596
(audience applauding)

346
00:22:53,679 --> 00:22:56,932
HENRYK (in German):
Wilhelm Melchior will be with us always...

347
00:22:57,600 --> 00:22:59,185
in his plays.

348
00:22:59,268 --> 00:23:00,394
(whispering)
Maria.

349
00:23:00,478 --> 00:23:05,357
I will have the privilege of performing them
here, in London, everywhere.

350
00:23:05,441 --> 00:23:08,944
So I say not “Farewell,” but...

351
00:23:09,028 --> 00:23:10,321
“See you, Wilhelm.”

352
00:23:10,404 --> 00:23:12,573
(audience applauding)

353
00:23:13,824 --> 00:23:17,870
URS (in German): Thank you, Henryk,
for that wonderful tribute.

354
00:23:17,953 --> 00:23:23,375
Now please welcome
an old friend of Wilhelm's.

355
00:23:23,459 --> 00:23:25,878
A warm round of applause for...

356
00:23:25,961 --> 00:23:27,630
Maria Enders!

357
00:23:27,713 --> 00:23:30,716
(audience applauding, cheering)

358
00:23:32,843 --> 00:23:34,428
(whistles)

359
00:23:40,184 --> 00:23:42,186
Thank you.

360
00:23:44,188 --> 00:23:46,357
Go get 'em, tiger.

361
00:23:47,608 --> 00:23:49,443
MARIA:
Thank you very much.

362
00:24:08,671 --> 00:24:10,965
- Hi.
- Good evening. Welcome.

363
00:24:13,092 --> 00:24:15,136
I'm honored to welcome you here.

364
00:24:15,219 --> 00:24:18,305
I wish it had been
under happier circumstances.

365
00:24:18,389 --> 00:24:20,266
It's, um -

366
00:24:20,349 --> 00:24:23,811
it's great to celebrate his work.
Especially today.

367
00:24:23,894 --> 00:24:27,314
I was eager that the city of Zurich
pay tribute to him.

368
00:24:27,398 --> 00:24:29,692
He was very grateful to you.
He told me so.

369
00:24:32,736 --> 00:24:35,156
Hey. She'll just be two seconds.

370
00:24:35,239 --> 00:24:37,825
I'm sure she's gonna be thrilled
to be relieved from officialdom.

371
00:24:38,576 --> 00:24:41,704
- You know that his last play was set in Zurich.
- Oh, yes.

372
00:24:42,371 --> 00:24:44,999
He paints a rather dire portrait
of our political class.

373
00:24:45,082 --> 00:24:46,542
That's an understatement.

374
00:24:46,625 --> 00:24:49,920
- You should know. Your character was evil.
-(chuckles)

375
00:24:50,004 --> 00:24:52,339
Klaus Diesterweg is here to see you.

376
00:24:54,300 --> 00:24:55,926
Excuse me. Sorry.

377
00:24:58,762 --> 00:25:01,056
I already told him no.

378
00:25:01,140 --> 00:25:04,518
- He's here just to see you.
- The project doesn't interest me. Okay?

379
00:25:04,602 --> 00:25:07,938
He's a great director. Just hear him out.
You don't have to do it.

380
00:25:08,022 --> 00:25:11,567
- He's probably the best of his generation.
- I know. We saw the same productions.

381
00:25:12,401 --> 00:25:16,405
If you'd like to go on chatting with the mayor
and Henryk, you can be my guest.

382
00:25:18,407 --> 00:25:20,117
- No, thank you.
-(chuckles)

383
00:25:22,161 --> 00:25:23,787
Okay.

384
00:25:23,871 --> 00:25:27,625
Do you mind if I cut out for a bit?
I'm just gonna meet Berndt.

385
00:25:27,708 --> 00:25:29,001
Berndt?

386
00:25:29,084 --> 00:25:31,378
- The photographer.
-(whistles)

387
00:25:31,462 --> 00:25:34,673
We're just going to find somewhere
a bit livelier. This place is a dead zone.

388
00:25:34,757 --> 00:25:37,635
Oh. No problem.
I don't plan to hang around.

389
00:25:38,219 --> 00:25:39,553
Enjoy.

390
00:25:43,557 --> 00:25:46,227
- Thank you for finding time for me.
-It's a pleasure to meet you.

391
00:25:46,310 --> 00:25:48,604
- I hope you don't find me too insistent.
- Not at all.

392
00:25:48,687 --> 00:25:52,149
I've seen quite a few of your productions.
I enjoy them, and...

393
00:25:52,983 --> 00:25:57,571
I know <i>we'll</i> find an opportunity
to work together in the future.

394
00:25:57,655 --> 00:25:59,323
Give me one more chance.

395
00:25:59,406 --> 00:26:00,991
Klaus.

396
00:26:04,245 --> 00:26:09,208
I played Sigrid in Maloja <i>Snake</i>
when I was 18.

397
00:26:09,291 --> 00:26:11,460
For me it was more than a role.

398
00:26:12,544 --> 00:26:14,922
In some way, I am still Sigrid.

399
00:26:15,005 --> 00:26:17,591
That's my point.
If Sigrid seduces Helena -

400
00:26:17,675 --> 00:26:21,428
And it has nothing to do with being a lesbian,
by the way. I've always been straight.

401
00:26:21,512 --> 00:26:23,597
That's not at all what I meant.

402
00:26:23,681 --> 00:26:25,766
Sigrid is free, beyond everything.

403
00:26:25,849 --> 00:26:28,269
And most of all,
she's disruptive, unpredictable.

404
00:26:28,352 --> 00:26:29,895
I know.

405
00:26:31,188 --> 00:26:34,692
And right or wrong, I've always
identified with that freedom.

406
00:26:35,693 --> 00:26:37,361
It's a way of, uh...

407
00:26:38,821 --> 00:26:40,489
protecting myself.

408
00:26:41,115 --> 00:26:42,449
Do you smoke?

409
00:26:42,533 --> 00:26:45,703
Uh, no, no. I - I try not to.

410
00:26:48,789 --> 00:26:51,166
And for you,
Helena embodies the opposite?

411
00:26:51,250 --> 00:26:53,836
Helena is 40.
She's runs a company.

412
00:26:53,919 --> 00:26:57,214
She falls head over heels in love
with a girl who doesn't love her

413
00:26:57,881 --> 00:26:59,425
and leads her to suicide.

414
00:26:59,508 --> 00:27:01,885
Yes. She's completely the opposite.

415
00:27:02,469 --> 00:27:06,974
But what is it that attracts Helena
to Sigrid, if they are so different?

416
00:27:07,057 --> 00:27:09,977
It's obvious. Her youth.

417
00:27:10,936 --> 00:27:15,316
Well, if you're telling me that I'm Helena's
age now, yeah, you're right, it's true.

418
00:27:15,399 --> 00:27:17,735
But that doesn't mean I can play her.

419
00:27:17,818 --> 00:27:19,987
The way I see Helena is totally different.

420
00:27:20,571 --> 00:27:24,283
Despite her bourgeois life,
despite her responsibilities,

421
00:27:24,366 --> 00:27:26,702
she's not the epitome of order

422
00:27:26,785 --> 00:27:29,330
and not at all the opposite of Sigrid.

423
00:27:29,413 --> 00:27:33,792
Well, she is married, with children,
her social life is a huge success,

424
00:27:33,876 --> 00:27:35,336
and she sacrifices it all.

425
00:27:35,419 --> 00:27:36,879
Yeah, she's destructive.

426
00:27:36,962 --> 00:27:40,758
Sigrid revives
this hidden violence in Helena.

427
00:27:40,841 --> 00:27:42,926
Was it hidden or tamed?

428
00:27:45,429 --> 00:27:48,307
Time's gone by
and she can't accept it.

429
00:27:48,390 --> 00:27:49,933
Me neither, I guess.

430
00:27:52,561 --> 00:27:54,396
There's no antagonism.

431
00:27:54,480 --> 00:27:57,816
It's the attraction of two women
with the same wound.

432
00:27:57,900 --> 00:28:00,235
Sigrid and Helena
are one and the same person.

433
00:28:00,944 --> 00:28:03,197
One and the same person.

434
00:28:03,280 --> 00:28:05,282
That's what the play is about.

435
00:28:06,950 --> 00:28:10,412
And because you were Sigrid,
only you can be Helena now.

436
00:28:10,496 --> 00:28:13,374
Hmm. How can you be so sure?

437
00:28:13,457 --> 00:28:16,460
You know as well as I do
that Wilhelm Melchior

438
00:28:16,543 --> 00:28:18,545
had been working
on a sequel for years.

439
00:28:18,629 --> 00:28:22,383
Yes, but it was about Sigrid
at 40 years old.

440
00:28:22,466 --> 00:28:26,136
No, it was about Sigrid
20 years later became Helena.

441
00:28:29,848 --> 00:28:32,976
(sighs)
So who's to play Sigrid?

442
00:28:34,144 --> 00:28:35,938
Jo-Ann Ellis.

443
00:28:37,064 --> 00:28:40,401
She did a superhero movie
that just opened in the States.

444
00:28:41,151 --> 00:28:43,237
- And besides that?
- Not much.

445
00:28:43,320 --> 00:28:48,075
She's 19. She's a lot more interesting
than her interviews and profiles.

446
00:28:48,158 --> 00:28:50,077
She has a theatrical background.

447
00:28:50,160 --> 00:28:53,163
She doesn't want to be
swallowed up by Hollywood.

448
00:28:54,331 --> 00:28:58,001
She admires you, and she's willing
to pull out of her other commitments.

449
00:29:03,090 --> 00:29:06,176
Well, I've listened carefully.

450
00:29:08,053 --> 00:29:10,889
But to be honest,
um, the role scares me.

451
00:29:10,973 --> 00:29:12,766
Helena scares me.

452
00:29:12,850 --> 00:29:15,227
I'm in the middle of a divorce.

453
00:29:15,310 --> 00:29:18,272
I feel alone and vulnerable.

454
00:29:18,355 --> 00:29:20,357
Probably too vulnerable to do this.

455
00:29:22,067 --> 00:29:24,820
If you refuse, <i>I'll</i> understand, but...

456
00:29:25,863 --> 00:29:27,865
it will be a missed opportunity.

457
00:29:28,824 --> 00:29:31,076
Especially for Wilhelm.
-(chuckles)

458
00:29:32,870 --> 00:29:34,705
I should get going.

459
00:29:42,379 --> 00:29:45,382
Excuse me,
but I won't be staying for dinner.

460
00:29:47,217 --> 00:29:49,261
Good evening, Maria.

461
00:29:49,344 --> 00:29:51,472
Klaus.

462
00:29:51,555 --> 00:29:53,474
I have another reason.

463
00:29:53,557 --> 00:29:55,184
Susan Rosenberg.

464
00:29:55,893 --> 00:29:57,811
She played Helena with me.

465
00:29:57,895 --> 00:29:59,980
I remember Susan Rosenberg.

466
00:30:00,731 --> 00:30:03,275
She died in a car accident a year after.

467
00:30:04,985 --> 00:30:10,073
It's a superstition. I've always associated
her death with Helena's suicide.

468
00:30:10,157 --> 00:30:13,660
She was a lousy actress who didn't
understand a thing about the role.

469
00:30:15,579 --> 00:30:17,498
But her conventional style of acting

470
00:30:17,581 --> 00:30:20,083
highlighted the modernity
of your performance.

471
00:30:21,084 --> 00:30:22,878
You should be grateful to her.

472
00:30:32,804 --> 00:30:34,598
Please sit down.

473
00:30:35,933 --> 00:30:37,601
Thank you.

474
00:30:40,729 --> 00:30:42,856
Oh, is there a way of changing this?

475
00:30:42,940 --> 00:30:46,276
- Can you put him in another place?
- I'm - I'm sorry. Oh, he's coming.

476
00:30:55,994 --> 00:30:58,997
(chattering)

477
00:31:02,626 --> 00:31:04,920
You were with Klaus Diesterweg.

478
00:31:05,003 --> 00:31:07,047
Are you going to accept his offer?

479
00:31:07,130 --> 00:31:09,383
- What offer?
- You know.

480
00:31:09,466 --> 00:31:10,968
He's a very good director.

481
00:31:11,051 --> 00:31:14,137
If he'd offered me a role,
I'd accept it on the spot.

482
00:31:14,221 --> 00:31:16,890
So that means, um, I should accept it?

483
00:31:16,974 --> 00:31:19,351
- God, no!
