mouthing off some generic
pop psychology seriously.

1044
01:09:29,389 --> 01:09:32,100
- Been there, done that.
-(sighs) I like it.

1045
01:09:32,183 --> 01:09:35,186
I know. I know you do. I'm sorry.

1046
01:09:36,646 --> 01:09:41,150
There's no less truth than
in a more supposedly serious film.

1047
01:09:41,234 --> 01:09:43,695
She goes deep into the darker side
of her character.

1048
01:09:43,778 --> 01:09:47,490
-(laughing loudly)
-it's daring. it's really daring.

1049
01:09:47,574 --> 01:09:50,451
In a - In a big movie like that,
it's fucking cool.

1050
01:09:50,535 --> 01:09:54,789
Well, she's got great presence,
but I don't see what's so daring about it.

1051
01:09:57,083 --> 01:09:59,210
Despite her superpowers...

1052
01:09:59,294 --> 01:10:00,837
(stifled laughing)

1053
01:10:01,963 --> 01:10:04,632
- Her superpowers.
- Yes, her superpowers.

1054
01:10:04,716 --> 01:10:07,719
- Her superpowers?
- Yes, her superpowers. So what?

1055
01:10:07,802 --> 01:10:11,264
It's a convention, but it's no dumber
than any other convention.

1056
01:10:11,347 --> 01:10:14,475
Despite her superpowers,
she's emotionally defenseless.

1057
01:10:14,559 --> 01:10:17,145
She's in love,
but she's not loved in return.

1058
01:10:17,228 --> 01:10:19,439
This impossible love for Sargon,
the Alliance's worst enemy,

1059
01:10:19,522 --> 01:10:21,232
leads her to betrayal and madness.

1060
01:10:21,316 --> 01:10:24,777
Fuckin' shit. Are you telling me
there's nothing there worth playing there?

1061
01:10:24,861 --> 01:10:27,280
I don't know. I don't know, Val.
I don't know.

1062
01:10:29,157 --> 01:10:30,658
Thank you.

1063
01:10:31,326 --> 01:10:33,369
She knows that it means her downfall,

1064
01:10:33,453 --> 01:10:35,580
but that is the ultimate truth
of her desire.

1065
01:10:35,663 --> 01:10:37,832
- WAITER: Cheers.
-It's fuckin' powerful.

1066
01:10:39,500 --> 01:10:42,795
Oh, my God.
I hate you sometimes so much.

1067
01:10:42,879 --> 01:10:45,590
You're making my head spin.

1068
01:10:46,507 --> 01:10:50,678
And Sargon?
You find him interesting too?

1069
01:10:53,348 --> 01:10:56,017
- Yeah, I do.
- Good.

1070
01:10:59,354 --> 01:11:02,148
No, Sargon sucks. it's -

1071
01:11:03,566 --> 01:11:05,193
Jesus Christ!

1072
01:11:09,197 --> 01:11:11,491
CROUPIER:
<i>Vos jeux, mesdames, messieurs.</i>

1073
01:11:12,742 --> 01:11:14,494
Last bets, thank you.

1074
01:11:15,787 --> 01:11:17,956
<i>No more. No more bets.
Rien ne va plus.</i>

1075
01:11:18,039 --> 01:11:19,540
All of it?

1076
01:11:20,041 --> 01:11:21,626
Ho!

1077
01:11:21,709 --> 01:11:25,171
Did you see that?
My magical door-opening powers?

1078
01:11:25,254 --> 01:11:27,048
I can open a door too.

1079
01:11:27,966 --> 01:11:29,968
Sure you can drive?

1080
01:11:30,051 --> 01:11:33,054
- I had the same drinks as you.
- That's my point.

1081
01:11:35,723 --> 01:11:37,517
(crashing)

1082
01:11:37,600 --> 01:11:40,228
(car alarm wailing)

1083
01:11:40,311 --> 01:11:42,313
(quietly)
Go, go' go!

1084
01:12:00,456 --> 01:12:02,208
So...

1085
01:12:02,291 --> 01:12:04,711
what you were saying earlier was that,

1086
01:12:05,586 --> 01:12:10,675
unlike Jo-Ann, I don't take
that kind of role seriously, hmm?

1087
01:12:10,758 --> 01:12:12,677
What? No.

1088
01:12:12,760 --> 01:12:15,430
I don't know what you're talking about.

1089
01:12:15,513 --> 01:12:17,974
That I have disdain for those characters

1090
01:12:18,057 --> 01:12:21,602
and their... cartoonish psychology,

1091
01:12:21,686 --> 01:12:23,688
but she doesn't.

1092
01:12:23,771 --> 01:12:26,190
- Mmm.
- Which makes her superior to me.

1093
01:12:26,274 --> 01:12:28,359
Uh-oh. Don't get jealous.

1094
01:12:28,443 --> 01:12:30,528
That's not an attractive quality.

1095
01:12:30,611 --> 01:12:33,781
She dives headfirst into
a character's ambiguities, but...

1096
01:12:35,116 --> 01:12:36,617
I don't.

1097
01:12:37,785 --> 01:12:41,080
That's why you admire what she does.

1098
01:12:42,373 --> 01:12:43,875
Yeah.

1099
01:12:43,958 --> 01:12:48,171
You know, I think that when you watch her
in a movie like the one we saw tonight,

1100
01:12:48,254 --> 01:12:51,966
there is... there is no distance there.

1101
01:12:52,050 --> 01:12:56,054
It's normal.
It's, uh... her culture. Right?

1102
01:12:56,137 --> 01:12:58,056
Yeah, agreed.

1103
01:12:58,139 --> 01:13:01,392
- What's wrong with my acting?
- Nothing.

1104
01:13:01,476 --> 01:13:04,437
What do I need to do
to make you admire me?

1105
01:13:04,520 --> 01:13:06,647
Do I think too much? Huh?

1106
01:13:06,731 --> 01:13:08,566
Am I too classical?

1107
01:13:08,649 --> 01:13:11,277
Not liberated like Jo-Ann?

1108
01:13:11,360 --> 01:13:14,280
You're here to talk to me,
so start talking.

1109
01:13:14,363 --> 01:13:15,406
Hmm?

1110
01:13:15,490 --> 01:13:18,117
I don't know. You...

1111
01:13:18,201 --> 01:13:21,037
You can't be as accomplished as you are

1112
01:13:21,120 --> 01:13:23,873
and as well-rounded as an actress
as you are

1113
01:13:24,749 --> 01:13:27,251
and still expect to hold on
to the privileges of youth.

1114
01:13:27,335 --> 01:13:28,795
It just doesn't work like that.

1115
01:13:28,878 --> 01:13:30,755
Oh!

1116
01:13:30,838 --> 01:13:32,590
So I'm allowed to not be old,

1117
01:13:32,673 --> 01:13:35,593
as long as I don't want to be young,
is that it?

1118
01:13:35,676 --> 01:13:38,179
Yeah. I don't know. I guess so.

1119
01:13:39,347 --> 01:13:41,349
Yes. Totally. Well put.

1120
01:13:45,436 --> 01:13:46,938
Fuck.

1121
01:13:52,944 --> 01:13:55,655
I think, maybe, good night.

1122
01:13:55,738 --> 01:13:57,240
(exhales)

1123
01:13:58,407 --> 01:14:00,159
Wait, wait! Wait.

1124
01:14:00,243 --> 01:14:02,537
Hey. Hey-

1125
01:14:03,454 --> 01:14:05,998
You - You didn't tell me
how it went with Berndt.

1126
01:14:08,334 --> 01:14:11,712
Yeah, well, you know, um, fuck Berndt.
(laughs)

1127
01:14:12,505 --> 01:14:14,298
I thought you wouldn't believe me anyway.

1128
01:14:14,382 --> 01:14:16,050
Try.

1129
01:14:16,134 --> 01:14:18,177
Maybe you'll manage to persuade me.

1130
01:14:18,803 --> 01:14:20,805
I'm... exhausted.

1131
01:14:20,888 --> 01:14:23,057
I don't know. I don't have the energy.

1132
01:14:24,517 --> 01:14:26,519
Okay. Good night.

1133
01:14:27,436 --> 01:14:29,272
Oh, I spoke to Jay.

1134
01:14:29,355 --> 01:14:32,358
He doesn't think
he can get me out of the contract.

1135
01:14:34,819 --> 01:14:36,487
Yeah, I figured.

1136
01:14:41,868 --> 01:14:44,537
Please knock when you enter my office.

1137
01:14:45,997 --> 01:14:47,498
You summoned me.

1138
01:14:47,582 --> 01:14:50,084
I didn't summon you.
I asked you to come.

1139
01:14:50,168 --> 01:14:51,711
What's the difference?

1140
01:14:51,794 --> 01:14:55,590
There's differences. When I summon you,
it's for professional reasons.

1141
01:14:55,673 --> 01:14:58,551
When I ask you to come,
it's for... personal reasons.

1142
01:14:58,634 --> 01:15:00,845
- So it's personal.
- Yes.

1143
01:15:00,928 --> 01:15:02,847
All the more reason not to knock.

1144
01:15:02,930 --> 01:15:05,474
Everyone knocks
before coming into my office.

1145
01:15:05,558 --> 01:15:09,061
I could have been in a meeting
or in a private call.

1146
01:15:09,145 --> 01:15:11,814
I'm surprised Josephine let you through.

1147
01:15:11,898 --> 01:15:14,817
I told Josephine it didn't concern her.
She understood perfectly well.

1148
01:15:14,901 --> 01:15:17,195
Understood what?

1149
01:15:17,278 --> 01:15:19,363
That we have a personal relationship.

1150
01:15:19,447 --> 01:15:22,074
Since when does Josephine know

1151
01:15:22,158 --> 01:15:24,911
that we have what you call
a personal relationship?

1152
01:15:24,994 --> 01:15:27,330
Don't be stupid. She has eyes.

1153
01:15:27,413 --> 01:15:30,833
- You want me to draw you a picture?
- Please don't draw me a picture.

1154
01:15:31,792 --> 01:15:34,712
I thought it was between you and me.

1155
01:15:34,795 --> 01:15:36,297
I'm appalled.

1156
01:15:37,924 --> 01:15:39,425
Who else knows?

1157
01:15:41,886 --> 01:15:44,013
I don't know,

1158
01:15:44,096 --> 01:15:47,308
but in an office,
word gets around pretty fast.

1159
01:15:47,391 --> 01:15:49,227
You hired me as your personal assistant.

1160
01:15:49,310 --> 01:15:51,312
I'm under-qualified.

1161
01:15:52,813 --> 01:15:55,983
Everyone understood right away
that I could come and go as I pleased.

1162
01:15:56,067 --> 01:15:59,445
I created a vacuum around you,
to keep my hold on you.

1163
01:15:59,528 --> 01:16:01,906
Created a vacuum...

1164
01:16:03,407 --> 01:16:05,076
to keep your hold.

1165
01:16:09,830 --> 01:16:11,916
Don't you realize?

1166
01:16:11,999 --> 01:16:13,501
No.

1167
01:16:13,584 --> 01:16:15,503
I don't see things that way.

1168
01:16:15,586 --> 01:16:18,005
Then everyone else got it before you did.

1169
01:16:34,689 --> 01:16:37,233
MARIA: Shall we stop here?

1170
01:16:37,316 --> 01:16:38,818
Sure.

1171
01:16:42,405 --> 01:16:44,907
Can you repeat Sigrid's last lines?

1172
01:16:45,700 --> 01:16:47,201
(grunts)

1173
01:16:50,871 --> 01:16:53,082
“Then everyone else got it before you did.

1174
01:16:55,376 --> 01:16:57,753
Helena pauses and stares at Sigrid.”

1175
01:16:59,255 --> 01:17:01,757
What started at my place that night...

1176
01:17:03,592 --> 01:17:05,553
I won't deny a thing.

1177
01:17:08,139 --> 01:17:10,182
I probably wanted it. I don't know.

1178
01:17:12,184 --> 01:17:14,687
It's as if you put this idea in my head.

1179
01:17:15,229 --> 01:17:18,941
If you allowed yourself to be manipulated,
it's because you wanted it.

1180
01:17:20,776 --> 01:17:23,029
- I don't want anything.
- Stop!

1181
01:17:23,112 --> 01:17:25,364
I can't stand
that condescending tone of yours.

1182
01:17:25,448 --> 01:17:28,242
You want to be clear? This can't go on.

1183
01:17:28,326 --> 01:17:30,828
- Whatever you say.
-It's - I've thought it over.

1184
01:17:30,911 --> 01:17:32,830
<i>-It's finished.
- So I'll</i> leave.

1185
01:17:32,913 --> 01:17:36,584
No, you'll stay. You do your job well.
I have no complaints.

1186
01:17:39,003 --> 01:17:41,505
- I stay, and it's finished.
- We stop.

1187
01:17:41,589 --> 01:17:43,758
- And act as if it never happened.
- Yes.

1188
01:17:43,841 --> 01:17:46,677
Helena, you're not capable of that.

1189
01:17:49,722 --> 01:17:52,266
If I stay, nothing will change.
You'll be my lover.

1190
01:17:53,351 --> 01:17:54,352
No.

1191
01:17:54,435 --> 01:17:58,189
You will. And <i>I'll</i> keep
driving everyone else away.

1192
01:17:58,272 --> 01:18:00,274
I'll have a tighter
and tighter hold on you.

1193
01:18:00,358 --> 01:18:02,360
- Is that what you want?
- No, not necessarily.

1194
01:18:02,443 --> 01:18:04,528
I'm just telling you how it is.

1195
01:18:04,612 --> 01:18:07,239
But if you want me to leave,
just say so.

1196
01:18:12,912 --> 01:18:15,331
She doesn't speak. Say it.

1197
01:18:15,414 --> 01:18:17,291
It's time.

1198
01:18:17,375 --> 01:18:19,502
End of act 2.

1199
01:18:24,048 --> 01:18:26,801
- You hungry?
- Yeah.

1200
01:18:32,139 --> 01:18:34,308
(laughing)

1201
01:18:46,237 --> 01:18:48,572
(laughing)
“You'll be my lover.

1202
01:18:51,325 --> 01:18:54,203
I'll keep driving everyone else away.

1203
01:18:54,286 --> 01:18:56,789
I'll have a tighter
and tighter hold on you.”

1204
01:18:56,872 --> 01:18:59,834
Honestly,
you don't find this ridiculous?

1205
01:18:59,917 --> 01:19:02,920
- Why, 'cause she speaks brutally?
- No, because it's phony.

1206
01:19:03,003 --> 01:19:04,505
I don't believe it.

1207
01:19:06,173 --> 01:19:09,051
So you don't think people can be blinded
by their own emotions.

1208
01:19:09,135 --> 01:19:11,679
No, I do, but not to that extent.

1209
01:19:11,762 --> 01:19:13,681
It's too theoretical.

1210
01:19:15,057 --> 01:19:16,809
Even a little stupid.

1211
01:19:18,853 --> 01:19:20,312
It's theater.

1212
01:19:20,396 --> 01:19:23,858
It's an interpretation of life.
It can be truer than life itself.

1213
01:19:24,859 --> 01:19:28,237
Sigrid puts Helena's desires into words.
She says the unspoken.

1214
01:19:28,320 --> 01:19:30,448
She... formulates it.

1215
01:19:30,531 --> 01:19:32,908
- Cruelly.
- Okay, cruelly.

1216
01:19:32,992 --> 01:19:35,578
Yeah, cruelly,
because she's up to no good.

1217
01:19:35,661 --> 01:19:37,621
You're not in the character's skin. You -

1218
01:19:37,705 --> 01:19:41,292
I have no choice. I have to be them.
I have to identify with them.

1219
01:19:41,375 --> 01:19:43,127
When it's phony, I - I feel it.

1220
01:19:43,210 --> 01:19:44,712
Viscerally.

1221
01:19:46,046 --> 01:19:48,799
(sighs)
it can be, uh...

1222
01:19:48,883 --> 01:19:51,552
literary, but still be true.

1223
01:19:53,888 --> 01:19:56,474
I can feel the difference.
I can hear it.

1224
01:20:21,415 --> 01:20:23,792
(bell jangling)

1225
01:20:27,838 --> 01:20:29,507
(goat bleating)

1226
01:20:32,927 --> 01:20:34,428
(goat bleats)

1227
01:20:43,687 --> 01:20:45,022
- Maria.
- Hmm?

1228
01:20:45,105 --> 01:20:47,483
We've got to go.
Sun's about to go down.

1229
01:20:53,739 --> 01:20:55,824
I know a shortcut a little further up.

1230
01:20:55,908 --> 01:20:59,787
It's steep, but, uh,
it'll take us straight to Val Fex.

1231
01:21:00,579 --> 01:21:03,415
- I thought Val Fex was that way.
- No,no,no.

1232
01:21:07,878 --> 01:21:10,047
VALENTINE:
You're sure this is the right path, huh?

1233
01:21:10,130 --> 01:21:13,384
MARIA: Well... actually, not really.

1234
01:21:13,467 --> 01:21:15,636
I'm not even sure it's a path.

1235
01:21:15,719 --> 01:21:18,722
Or we might have forked off
somewhere, I don't know.

1236
01:21:19,848 --> 01:21:21,809
I think you're right.

1237
01:21:23,102 --> 01:21:27,439
I'm pretty sure Val Fex
is, um... not this way.

1238
01:21:30,317 --> 01:21:32,987
Anyway, we're heading down.
We'll end up somewhere.

1239
01:21:35,614 --> 01:21:38,117
I think this road takes us to Maloja.

1240
01:21:40,452 --> 01:21:42,788
What do we do when we get to Maloja?

1241
01:21:43,914 --> 01:21:45,833
We take the bus.

1242
01:21:50,462 --> 01:21:54,341
You know, you don't have to keep me on
if you find my ideas simplistic.

1243
01:21:56,510 --> 01:21:58,178
What makes you say that?

1244
01:21:59,179 --> 01:22:03,684
If you find my point of view...
uninteresting, I -

1245
01:22:05,894 --> 01:22:08,480
I don't really know what I'm doing here. I...

1246
01:22:09,523 --> 01:22:12,651
I can run lines with you,
but I don't really see the point.

1247
01:22:12,735 --> 01:22:14,278
You can find anyone to do that.

1248
01:22:14,361 --> 01:22:17,948
No, all I'm saying is that thinking about a text
is different from living it.

1249
01:22:18,032 --> 01:22:20,034
It's nothing against you.

1250
01:22:20,117 --> 01:22:21,785
Y-You...

1251
01:22:21,869 --> 01:22:23,871
You hate the play. You hate her.

1252
01:22:27,333 --> 01:22:29,793
You don't have to take it out on me.

1253
01:22:29,877 --> 01:22:31,712
I'm just doing my job.

1254
01:22:45,601 --> 01:22:46,894
Ready?

1255
01:22:48,520 --> 01:22:50,022
- You're ready?
- Yes!

1256
01:22:57,404 --> 01:22:59,073
Don't lie to me!

1257
01:22:59,156 --> 01:23:03,202
You received a confirmation
for a flight to Tokyo.

1258
01:23:03,285 --> 01:23:05,996
You're reading my mail now?
Aren't you ashamed?

1259
01:23:06,080 --> 01:23:08,540
I haven't felt shame in a long time.

1260
01:23:08,624 --> 01:23:10,834
I went through all your desk drawers,
your notebooks,

1261
01:23:10,918 --> 01:23:13,337
and I'm doing it
because you want to leave me.

1262
01:23:13,420 --> 01:23:15,339
Now I know when and how.

1263
01:23:15,422 --> 01:23:19,134
Helena is restless.
Sigrid remains poised.

1264
01:23:19,218 --> 01:23:21,011
All you had to do was ask.

1265
01:23:21,095 --> 01:23:24,682
Yes, I accepted a job in Tokyo.
A pharmaceutical lab.

1266
01:23:24,765 --> 01:23:27,685
I think <i>it'll</i> be much more interesting
than the work I'm doing here.

1267
01:23:27,768 --> 01:23:30,521
More interesting
than what you're doing here?

1268
01:23:30,604 --> 01:23:34,400
Haven't I given into
every demand you've made?

1269
01:23:34,483 --> 01:23:38,362
No other company would have given you
that kind of responsibility and power!

1270
01:23:38,445 --> 01:23:40,322
Exactly.

1271
01:23:40,406 --> 01:23:42,616
It's weighing on me.

1272
01:23:42,700 --> 01:23:44,785
I know this place in and out.

1273
01:23:44,868 --> 01:23:49,164
The world moves. I want to feel that.
I want to be a part of it.

1274
01:23:49,915 --> 01:23:52,876
I want to travel.
Switzerland's too provincial.

1275
01:23:52,960 --> 01:23:55,045
(screams)

1276
01:23:55,129 --> 01:23:57,840
(crying)

1277
01:24:01,969 --> 01:24:03,971
(crying continues)

1278
01:24:05,723 --> 01:24:08,892
She takes a deep breath
and regains her composure.

1279
01:24:08,976 --> 01:24:11,103
And with me you don't feel free?

1280
01:24:11,729 --> 01:24:14,273
You've become too dependent on me.

1281
01:24:14,356 --> 01:24:17,234
It's unhealthy.
What do I get in return?

1282
01:24:17,317 --> 01:24:19,737
I give you whatever you want.
You know that.

1283
01:24:19,820 --> 01:24:21,071
Oh.

1284
01:24:21,155 --> 01:24:24,575
Like a job at a dead-end company
that's about to go down the drain?

1285
01:24:24,658 --> 01:24:26,994
How could you say... a thing like that?

1286
01:24:27,077 --> 01:24:29,288
Open your eyes, my poor Helena.

1287
01:24:29,371 --> 01:24:30,914
I'm not your poor Helena!

1288
01:24:30,998 --> 01:24:35,711
- Nothing I've learned here is of any use to me.
- I'm not your poor Helena!

1289
01:24:35,794 --> 01:24:37,755
You'll never last.

1290
01:24:37,838 --> 01:24:40,382
You should listen to what
the bankers are telling you.

1291
01:24:40,466 --> 01:24:41,925
And your board members.

1292
01:24:42,009 --> 01:24:45,179
That's not true! For God's sake.

1293
01:24:46,597 --> 01:24:50,225
Oh, this relationship
between these women, it's - it's...

1294
01:24:50,893 --> 01:24:52,644
Fuck. it's disturbing.

1295
01:24:52,728 --> 01:24:54,229
MARIA: Disturbing.

1296
01:24:54,313 --> 01:24:56,231
Nowadays people say “disturbing”
about everything,

1297
01:24:56,315 --> 01:24:58,984
even the most conventional ideas.
(laughing)

1298
01:24:59,067 --> 01:25:02,112
Anyway, it's, uh - it's a male fantasy.

1299
01:25:02,196 --> 01:25:04,531
Uh, no, it's not.

1300
01:25:04,615 --> 01:25:07,159
I don't know why
I should be helping to bring it alive.

1301
01:25:07,242 --> 01:25:10,329
I bet you weren't saying stuff like this
when you were playing Sigrid.

1302
01:25:10,412 --> 01:25:12,831
I was a kid when I was playing Sigrid.

1303
01:25:12,915 --> 01:25:16,293
L-I wasn't asking those kind of questions.

1304
01:25:16,376 --> 01:25:18,295
Like Jo-Ann in her science-fiction film.

1305
01:25:18,378 --> 01:25:20,005
Yeah, probably.

1306
01:25:22,090 --> 01:25:24,635
Don't you want to get that innocence back?

1307
01:25:24,718 --> 01:25:26,470
You can't get innocent twice.

1308
01:25:26,553 --> 01:25:28,096
You can.

1309
01:25:28,180 --> 01:25:30,891
If you just accepted Helena
the way you accepted Sigrid.

1310
01:25:30,974 --> 01:25:34,478
Obviously, it's easier to relate to strength
rather than weakness.

1311
01:25:34,561 --> 01:25:36,730
Youth is better than maturity.

1312
01:25:36,814 --> 01:25:39,942
Cruelty is cool, suffering sucks.

1313
01:25:41,568 --> 01:25:43,320
But she's...

1314
01:25:43,403 --> 01:25:45,906
She's mature and she's innocent.

1315
01:25:45,989 --> 01:25:48,909
She's innocent in her own way.
That's what I like about her.

1316
01:25:54,581 --> 01:25:56,708
I'll make some coffee.
You want some?

1317
01:25:59,127 --> 01:26:01,505
Cruelty is cool and suffering sucks.

1318
01:26:20,190 --> 01:26:22,693
You didn't answer me.

1319
01:26:22,776 --> 01:26:27,072
You have your interpretation of the play.
I think mine's just confusing you.

1320
01:26:28,448 --> 01:26:30,117
It's frustrating me.

1321
01:26:31,118 --> 01:26:32,619
It's uncomfortable.

1322
01:26:32,703 --> 01:26:34,371
It's not good.

1323
01:26:42,921 --> 01:26:44,214
Stay.

1324
01:26:44,298 --> 01:26:45,799
(sighs)

1325
01:26:48,135 --> 01:26:49,970
No. No.

1326
01:26:50,053 --> 01:26:51,972
Please, stay.

1327
01:26:53,515 --> 01:26:55,183
I need you.

1328
01:27:10,324 --> 01:27:12,826
<i>N</i> (classical)

1329
01:27:21,752 --> 01:27:23,754
<i>N</i> (continues)

1330
01:27:43,523 --> 01:27:45,484
(whispers, inaudible)

1331
01:27:48,737 --> 01:27:50,739
(whispers, inaudible)

1332
01:28:35,784 --> 01:28:37,160
Thank you.

1333
01:28:37,244 --> 01:28:40,747
I prefer 18th-century music to any other.

1334
01:28:40,831 --> 01:28:42,874
It's so bright and lively.

1335
01:28:42,958 --> 01:28:46,920
Yeah, me too. Romantic music
is so sad and depressing.

1336
01:28:47,004 --> 01:28:49,881
But I'd rather listen to rock music
any day of the week though.

1337
01:28:49,965 --> 01:28:51,550
- Even the worst.
- Not me.

1338
01:28:51,633 --> 01:28:54,011
I've heard too much of it.
I'm sick of it.

1339
01:28:54,094 --> 01:28:56,513
Well, you're such a snob.

1340
01:28:56,596 --> 01:29:00,475
No. Tastes can get worn out,
kind of like desire.

1341
01:29:02,352 --> 01:29:05,480
I've never listened to Handel properly.
I think he's excellent.

1342
01:29:05,564 --> 01:29:08,108
I haven't been this moved
by music in ages.

1343
01:29:09,943 --> 01:29:11,653
You're making fun of me.

1344
01:29:11,737 --> 01:29:13,655
I'm not, but I just...

1345
01:29:15,282 --> 01:29:18,618
I find it really cute that you're trying
to fit in with my ideas.

1346
01:29:18,702 --> 01:29:20,996
But you know I'm not a music whiz.

1347
01:29:21,079 --> 01:29:23,874
I mean, besides what my family
practically spoon-fed me,

1348
01:29:23,957 --> 01:29:25,876
which is incredibly specialized,

1349
01:29:25,959 --> 01:29:28,587
I don't know a thing about music.

1350
01:29:30,630 --> 01:29:32,132
Thank you.

1351
01:29:32,883 --> 01:29:35,469
So, how'd it go with your wife?

1352
01:29:35,552 --> 01:29:37,262
Really well.

1353
01:29:37,345 --> 01:29:39,723
No, I'm kidding. It was horrible.

1354
01:29:39,806 --> 01:29:44,061
But, you know, she's... she's not the type
to wear her heart on her sleeve.

1355
01:29:44,144 --> 01:29:46,146
I think she was expecting it.

1356
01:29:46,229 --> 01:29:48,982
- Did you tell her about me?
- No, I said, you know,

1357
01:29:49,066 --> 01:29:52,652
I'd be going off on my own to write my book
and wouldn't be back.

1358
01:29:52,736 --> 01:29:54,488
She must be suspecting something.

1359
01:29:54,571 --> 01:29:56,823
She has no idea
you and I know each other.

1360
01:29:56,907 --> 01:29:59,367
Well, she will.
I mean, once it hits the tabloids.

1361
01:29:59,451 --> 01:30:02,746
- They're not going to find us here.
- They're going to find us anywhere.

1362
01:30:02,829 --> 01:30:04,498
It's their job, you know.

1363
01:30:04,581 --> 01:30:06,583
Did you say anything to Maria Enders?

1364
01:30:06,666 --> 01:30:09,920
Just that I would be taking advantage
of my press tour and come say hi.

1365
01:30:10,003 --> 01:30:12,089
She didn't find that strange?

1366
01:30:12,172 --> 01:30:16,176
I talked to her assistant, and she didn't
seem to question it, so I guess not.

1367
01:30:27,229 --> 01:30:29,439
♪♪ (jazz, faint)

1368
01:30:31,525 --> 01:30:33,527
Hey. There she is, just there.

1369
01:30:34,027 --> 01:30:36,113
- Hi.
- Hi. Hi.

1370
01:30:36,196 --> 01:30:38,448
- Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you too.

1371
01:30:38,532 --> 01:30:40,117
- Wow.
- What?

1372
01:30:40,200 --> 01:30:43,453
- I never would have recognized you.
- Really?

1373
01:30:43,537 --> 01:30:46,373
I mean, if you've only seen me
on the Internet or in movies,

1374
01:30:46,456 --> 01:30:48,959
-that's not really a big surprise.
- Still, it's a little weird.

1375
01:30:49,042 --> 01:30:51,920
You, on the other hand,
look exactly like all your roles.

1376
01:30:52,003 --> 01:30:54,131
(chuckles)
I hope not all of them.

1377
01:30:54,214 --> 01:30:56,800
No,no,no.
Only the better, only the better ones.

1378
01:30:56,883 --> 01:30:58,802
Rest assured,
you don't look like Nemesis.

1379
01:30:58,885 --> 01:31:02,097
-(all laughing)
- This is Chris. He's a... He's a novelist.

1380
01:31:02,180 --> 01:31:04,474
Hi. Nice to meet you, Chris.
My assistant.

1381
01:31:04,558 --> 01:31:07,144
Hey. it's so good to meet both of you.
Seriously.

1382
01:31:07,227 --> 01:31:08,520
Yeah.

1383
01:31:08,603 --> 01:31:11,857
Hello. May I get you anything to drink?

1384
01:31:11,940 --> 01:31:13,859
- A cognac for me, please.
- Yeah?

1385
01:31:13,942 --> 01:31:15,610
<i>- I'll</i> have the same.
- Okay.

1386
01:31:15,694 --> 01:31:17,404
- I'm fine, thanks.
- All right.

1387
01:31:17,487 --> 01:31:19,489
What herbal teas do you have?

1388
01:31:19,573 --> 01:31:22,325
We have vervain, mint and chamomile.

1389
01:31:22,409 --> 01:31:24,578
- Um, can I get a chamomile, please?
- Yeah, sure.

1390
01:31:24,661 --> 01:31:26,163
Thank you.

1391
01:31:27,414 --> 01:31:32,502
(sighs) I don't think you understand
how much of an honor this is for me.

1392
01:31:32,586 --> 01:31:34,963
When I was 15, I saw...

1393
01:31:35,046 --> 01:31:38,341
Oh, my God, the movie you did
with the CIA and Harrison Ford.

1394
01:31:38,425 --> 01:31:40,010
- I'm so sorry. I'm blanking.
- Um...

1395
01:31:40,093 --> 01:31:43,221
<i>Beetle on Its Back.
- A Beetle on Its Back, with Harrison</i> Ford.

1396
01:31:43,305 --> 01:31:44,764
You blew my mind.

1397
01:31:44,848 --> 01:31:46,808
You -You...

1398
01:31:46,892 --> 01:31:48,518
You were the epitome of class.

1399
01:31:48,602 --> 01:31:51,271
You were everything
I ever wanted to be as an actress.

1400
01:31:51,354 --> 01:31:53,773
And I mean, the way that you
battled those politicians

1401
01:31:53,857 --> 01:31:56,359
and the military brass men,
it was captivating.

1402
01:31:56,443 --> 01:31:59,863
It was my first Hollywood film.
I was a little lost.

1403
01:31:59,946 --> 01:32:03,241
Um... Sydney Pollack was really nice,

1404
01:32:03,325 --> 01:32:05,702
but sometimes I didn't understand
what he was saying,

1405
01:32:05,785 --> 01:32:07,579
so I was too shy to ask.

1406
01:32:07,662 --> 01:32:10,165
But fortunately,
Harrison was there to help.

1407
01:32:10,248 --> 01:32:12,542
-(laughing)
- A lot.

1408
01:32:14,377 --> 01:32:16,046
Well, then of course, after that,

1409
01:32:16,129 --> 01:32:19,466
I begged my parents to let me
see you on stage, in The <i>Seagull.</i>

1410
01:32:19,549 --> 01:32:23,386
And they didn't know who you were
before then, because...

1411
01:32:23,470 --> 01:32:25,347
well, they kind of hate movies.

1412
01:32:25,430 --> 01:32:28,225
- Well, I hope they tolerate the theater.
- No,no,no.

1413
01:32:28,308 --> 01:32:31,937
They don't just tolerate the theater.
I mean, they're absolutely in love with it.

1414
01:32:32,020 --> 01:32:34,689
In fact, they see everything and... and...

1415
01:32:34,773 --> 01:32:36,733
Well, you know,
when they saw your performance,

1416
01:32:36,816 --> 01:32:39,402
they said it was the best Nina
they'd ever seen.

1417
01:32:39,486 --> 01:32:41,571
And that meant a lot to me.

1418
01:32:41,655 --> 01:32:43,823
Because after -
You know, before that I -

1419
01:32:43,907 --> 01:32:47,244
I'd never been able to tell them
that I wanted to be an actress.

1420
01:32:47,327 --> 01:32:50,080
But because of you,
I could pursue my vocation.

1421
01:32:50,163 --> 01:32:52,332
I prefer your early French films.

1422
01:32:52,415 --> 01:32:54,668
There was a cycle at the ICA in London.

1423
01:32:54,751 --> 01:32:56,753
I saw almost all of them.

1424
01:32:56,836 --> 01:32:59,256
And you came.
You probably don't remember.

1425
01:32:59,339 --> 01:33:02,008
Oh, I remember perfectly well.

1426
01:33:02,092 --> 01:33:05,762
I was fascinated by how freely
you spoke about your work.

1427
01:33:05,845 --> 01:33:09,975
And, um, yet someone asked you
if you had any regrets,

1428
01:33:10,058 --> 01:33:13,478
and you said, “We're not allowed
to regret anything.

1429
01:33:13,561 --> 01:33:16,773
If we're sincere, then we're
the sum total of our experiences,

1430
01:33:16,856 --> 01:33:18,358
with no exceptions.”

1431
01:33:19,067 --> 01:33:20,694
I said that?

1432
01:33:20,777 --> 01:33:22,988
Well, not word for word.
Something like that.

1433
01:33:23,071 --> 01:33:26,366
- You don't think that anymore?
- Oh, I... No.

1434
01:33:26,449 --> 01:33:30,704
I completely agree with that, 100%.

1435
01:33:30,787 --> 01:33:33,123
(all laughing)

1436
01:33:34,124 --> 01:33:37,460
You know, I am incredibly intimidated
to take on your role.

1437
01:33:37,544 --> 01:33:40,964
I mean, no one's going to
be able to do it like you did.

1438
01:33:41,047 --> 01:33:43,216
- I hope you don't judge me too harshly.
- Oh.

1439
01:33:43,300 --> 01:33:45,885
We all have our own way into a character.
They're all good.

1440
01:33:45,969 --> 01:33:48,972
Well, I cannot wait to do
the read-through tomorrow.

1441
01:33:49,055 --> 01:33:51,683
<i>We'll</i> work in Wilhelm's chalet.
I hope that's okay with you.

1442
01:33:51,766 --> 01:33:55,645
Yeah, sure, as long as his ghost
isn't watching over us the entire time.

1443
01:33:55,729 --> 01:33:59,149
I can't promise you that, but don't worry.
He's a well-meaning ghost.

1444
01:33:59,232 --> 01:34:02,152
Ooh. Well-meaning?
I don't know about that.

1445
01:34:02,235 --> 01:34:03,903
Nor do l.

1446
01:34:05,447 --> 01:34:09,951
You know, it's incredibly brave of you
to take on the role of Helena.

1447
01:34:10,035 --> 01:34:13,580
It's... it's a way of dealing with time.

1448
01:34:13,663 --> 01:34:16,666
Yes, well, I don't know, sometimes I...

1449
01:34:18,585 --> 01:34:21,129
I tell myself that it's just a job.

1450
01:34:21,212 --> 01:34:24,174
And I'll be happy to move on
when it's over.

1451
01:34:25,383 --> 01:34:27,677
Hey. Thank you.

1452
01:34:27,761 --> 01:34:30,847
You still want to see the snake
you asked me the other day?

1453
01:34:30,930 --> 01:34:32,265
Oh, yeah.

1454
01:34:32,349 --> 01:34:35,018
The weather they're predicting
for tomorrow seems ideal.

1455
01:34:35,101 --> 01:34:37,562
So you better make sure
you're out there at daybreak.

1456
01:34:37,645 --> 01:34:40,482
It's wonderful to see it
coming over the Maloja Pass.

1457
01:34:40,565 --> 01:34:42,359
Great. Awesome. That's amazing.

1458
01:34:42,442 --> 01:34:44,235
- Thank you.
- Okay.

1459
01:34:45,487 --> 01:34:47,572
I thought they were really nice.

1460
01:34:49,157 --> 01:34:53,661
It's true. I... She's a lot more interesting
than the person you described.

1461
01:34:54,537 --> 01:34:56,581
I didn't know her parents were musicians.

1462
01:34:56,664 --> 01:34:58,792
I liked him '[00. He's...

1463
01:34:58,875 --> 01:35:00,710
(car door opens)

1464
01:35:00,794 --> 01:35:03,755
-(laughs)
- What's so funny? Did I say something funny?

1465
01:35:05,256 --> 01:35:08,051
They spent the whole evening
flattering you.

1466
01:35:08,134 --> 01:35:09,594
Of course you liked them.

1467
01:35:09,677 --> 01:35:12,555
- That has nothing to do with it.
- No, no. Of course not.

1468
01:35:12,639 --> 01:35:14,474
(laughing)

1469
01:35:22,816 --> 01:35:25,235
-(laughing)
- What was that movie again?

1470
01:35:27,070 --> 01:35:29,906
<i>Beetle on Its Back!</i>

1471
01:35:29,989 --> 01:35:31,991
<i>What was that meme'?
Beetle on Its Back!</i>

1472
01:35:32,075 --> 01:35:34,077
(Maria laughing)

1473
01:35:35,495 --> 01:35:37,539
I can't believe we got this scoop tonight.

1474
01:35:37,622 --> 01:35:39,082
What scoop?

1475
01:35:39,165 --> 01:35:41,459
She's with Christopher Giles.

1476
01:35:41,543 --> 01:35:44,170
Chris? His name is Christopher Giles?

1477
01:35:44,254 --> 01:35:46,464
- Yes.
- Is he famous?

1478
01:35:46,548 --> 01:35:49,259
He's... fiber-famous!

1479
01:35:50,218 --> 01:35:53,388
I can't remember
which major book prize he won, but...

1480
01:35:54,848 --> 01:35:58,601
He's married. He's with Dorothea
Von Duisburg, the German artist.

1481
01:35:59,602 --> 01:36:01,896
She had a show
at the Serpentine last year.

1482
01:36:05,442 --> 01:36:07,777
Never heard of either of them.

1483
01:36:10,029 --> 01:36:12,282
You should Google him.

1484
01:36:12,365 --> 01:36:14,617
How do you spell his name?

1485
01:36:14,701 --> 01:36:17,287
Giles. G-I-L-E-S.

1486
01:36:17,370 --> 01:36:19,706
Well, he's obviously with her.

1487
01:36:21,374 --> 01:36:22,625
Yeah.

1488
01:36:22,709 --> 01:36:26,504
When word gets out,
it's going to be, like, a tsunami.

1489
01:36:28,631 --> 01:36:30,633
Well, yeah, on their planet.

1490
01:36:30,717 --> 01:36:33,011
Their planet has a name.

1491
01:36:33,094 --> 01:36:35,555
It's called the real world.
Welcome!

1492
01:36:38,057 --> 01:36:40,977
Careful with that.
Come here. Give that to me.

1493
01:36:41,060 --> 01:36:42,687
(Maria laughing loudly)

1494
01:36:42,770 --> 01:36:44,272
Here.

1495
01:36:59,996 --> 01:37:02,832
MARIA: I spent all night thinking
about Helena's death.

1496
01:37:03,833 --> 01:37:05,376
Her death?

1497
01:37:05,460 --> 01:37:09,339
She doesn't necessarily die.
She just... She disappears.

1498
01:37:09,422 --> 01:37:11,257
That's your interpretation.

1499
01:37:11,341 --> 01:37:14,511
Well, it's... it's pretty ambiguous.

1500
01:37:14,594 --> 01:37:17,013
She goes out for a hike
and never comes back.

1501
01:37:17,096 --> 01:37:19,516
Seems clear enough to me.

1502
01:37:19,599 --> 01:37:21,476
You don't know that.

1503
01:37:21,559 --> 01:37:23,603
She could reinvent herself
somewhere else.

1504
01:37:23,686 --> 01:37:25,271
There's really no way of knowing.

1505
01:37:25,355 --> 01:37:27,357
Yeah, you can imagine
whatever you want.

1506
01:37:27,440 --> 01:37:29,234
Are we going the right way?

1507
01:37:29,317 --> 01:37:32,028
I mean, I don't mind waking up
at the crack of dawn,

1508
01:37:32,111 --> 01:37:34,822
but not to get lost in the mountains
and miss the snake.

1509
01:37:34,906 --> 01:37:37,242
Well, we're basically here. You happy?

1510
01:37:37,325 --> 01:37:39,869
What makes you think we're here?

1511
01:37:39,953 --> 01:37:42,455
I've got a map!
You want me to show you?

1512
01:37:42,539 --> 01:37:44,040
Come here.

1513
01:37:45,917 --> 01:37:48,962
This is the bend we just went around
10 minutes ago.

1514
01:37:49,045 --> 01:37:52,006
And just around there
is the view of the valley. You see that?

1515
01:37:52,090 --> 01:37:54,759
- How do you know?
- How do -

1516
01:37:56,469 --> 01:37:59,847
Such a fucking pain in the ass.
Jesus Christ.

1517
01:38:00,890 --> 01:38:03,768
I don't know why you're so dead set
on making this play

1518
01:38:03,851 --> 01:38:06,271
say the opposite
of what it was meant to say.

1519
01:38:06,354 --> 01:38:08,314
At 20,

1520
01:38:08,398 --> 01:38:11,067
you saw Sigrid's ambition
and you saw her violence

1521
01:38:11,150 --> 01:38:12,902
because you felt it in yourself.

1522
01:38:12,986 --> 01:38:15,572
- So?
- That's what I'm saying.

1523
01:38:15,655 --> 01:38:18,032
The text is like an object.

1524
01:38:18,116 --> 01:38:20,660
It's gonna change perspective
based on where you're standing.

1525
01:38:21,619 --> 01:38:23,121
I don't know.

1526
01:38:25,415 --> 01:38:27,584
We should go.
We're gonna miss the snake.

1527
01:38:27,667 --> 01:38:29,794
There won't be any snake.

1528
01:38:31,754 --> 01:38:33,256
Fuck it.

1529
01:39:23,765 --> 01:39:25,266
Look there!

1530
01:39:26,434 --> 01:39:28,436
Is that the snake?

1531
01:39:30,438 --> 01:39:32,815
No.

1532
01:39:32,899 --> 01:39:35,276
No, it's just mist.

1533
01:39:35,360 --> 01:39:37,654
A little fog.

1534
01:39:37,737 --> 01:39:39,697
But it breaks up.

1535
01:39:42,367 --> 01:39:44,994
Still pretty beautiful though.

1536
01:39:45,078 --> 01:39:48,748
It's like it's gathering
and pouring out into the valley.

1537
01:39:50,750 --> 01:39:52,919
Maybe it is the snake.

1538
01:39:55,004 --> 01:39:57,090
We have to be patient.

1539
01:39:59,467 --> 01:40:02,303
No, it's not the snake.

1540
01:40:02,387 --> 01:40:04,347
Oh, yes!

1541
01:40:04,430 --> 01:40:07,517
I think it's turning into the snake!

1542
01:40:07,600 --> 01:40:09,602
How 'bout you?

1543
01:40:10,603 --> 01:40:12,105
Val?

1544
01:40:13,731 --> 01:40:15,775
What the hell are you doing?

1545
01:40:17,985 --> 01:40:19,862
Val?

1546
01:40:21,489 --> 01:40:22,990
Val!

1547
01:40:24,117 --> 01:40:25,618
Val!

1548
01:40:27,453 --> 01:40:28,955
Val!

1549
01:40:32,709 --> 01:40:34,210
Val!

1550
01:40:35,002 --> 01:40:36,879
Answer me!

1551
01:40:38,965 --> 01:40:40,466
Val!

1552
01:40:44,387 --> 01:40:46,055
Val!

1553
01:40:47,765 --> 01:40:52,270
<i>♪♪ (classical)</i>

1554
01:42:08,805 --> 01:42:11,140
<i>How's the hotel?</i>

1555
01:42:11,224 --> 01:42:14,227
The hotel's fine.
Oh, thanks for the flowers.

1556
01:42:14,310 --> 01:42:17,772
<i>So, did you reach Klaus?
He was really impatient to see you.</i>

1557
01:42:17,855 --> 01:42:20,983
<i>You have to return his calls, you know.
He thinks you're avoiding him.</i>

1558
01:42:21,067 --> 01:42:23,820
We're having dinner.
He's a half hour late.

1559
01:42:23,903 --> 01:42:26,572
<i>Oh, so you called me to kill time.</i>

1560
01:42:26,656 --> 01:42:28,241
<i>Just kidding.</i>

1561
01:42:28,324 --> 01:42:31,702
I'm not avoiding him
I - I want to talk to him one-on-one.

1562
01:42:31,786 --> 01:42:34,413
You know how reluctant I was.
I'm over that now.

1563
01:42:34,497 --> 01:42:37,166
<i>You know, Klaus understands
the risks you're taking.</i>

1564
01:42:37,250 --> 01:42:41,087
<i>I know he's sincere. He's doing this
for you and for Wilhelm's memory.</i>

1565
01:42:41,170 --> 01:42:43,256
And for the publicity.

1566
01:42:43,339 --> 01:42:45,591
Twenty years after being Sigrid,
I'm Helena.

1567
01:42:45,675 --> 01:42:48,469
That's all the press is talking about.

1568
01:42:48,553 --> 01:42:51,305
You know, he's like every artist
of his generation.

1569
01:42:51,389 --> 01:42:53,516
He has a flair for PR.

1570
01:42:53,599 --> 01:42:55,184
<i>Oh, and is that a crime?</i>

1571
01:42:55,268 --> 01:42:59,981
To excel and to know how to show it
is to excel twice.

1572
01:43:00,064 --> 01:43:02,066
Baltasar Gracián said that.

1573
01:43:02,149 --> 01:43:06,028
<i>I have no idea who that is,
but he was right.</i>

1574
01:43:06,112 --> 01:43:08,698
<i>The press is talking about you
and your work.</i>

1575
01:43:08,781 --> 01:43:12,034
Oh, I said okay to pictures. No interviews.
It's too soon, too fragile.

1576
01:43:12,118 --> 01:43:14,120
-(phone rings)
- Hold on.

1577
01:43:15,079 --> 01:43:16,831
Yes?

1578
01:43:18,040 --> 01:43:19,959
Tell him I'm on my way down.

1579
01:43:20,042 --> 01:43:21,544
Thank you.

1580
01:43:22,962 --> 01:43:25,965
<i>- It's Klaus.
- You 'll be fine.</i>

1581
01:43:28,968 --> 01:43:30,136
Hi.

1582
01:43:31,554 --> 01:43:32,763
- Hi.
- Hi.

1583
01:43:32,847 --> 01:43:36,517
Excuse me, I'm late.
But something terrible has happened.

1584
01:43:36,601 --> 01:43:39,228
Dorothea tried to commit suicide.
She's in a coma.

1585
01:43:39,312 --> 01:43:40,771
Dorothea?

1586
01:43:40,855 --> 01:43:43,316
Christopher Giles's wife.

1587
01:43:43,399 --> 01:43:46,694
Chris. Um, Jo-Ann's friend, you mean?

1588
01:43:46,777 --> 01:43:49,655
Yes, but you are not supposed
to know he's Jo-Ann's friend.

1589
01:43:49,739 --> 01:43:51,657
Well, they were together in Sils, so...

1590
01:43:51,741 --> 01:43:55,912
I thought it was more recent than that.
Excuse me, sir. We can go.

1591
01:43:55,995 --> 01:43:59,707
Well, she slit her wrists in her studio.

1592
01:43:59,790 --> 01:44:02,793
The housekeeper found her
in a pool of her own blood.

1593
01:44:02,877 --> 01:44:04,629
Oh, that's awful.

1594
01:44:06,088 --> 01:44:07,924
She's a well-known artist, right?

1595
01:44:08,007 --> 01:44:10,092
Dorothea is an amazing girl.

1596
01:44:10,176 --> 01:44:13,387
Beautiful, talented,
everything going for her.

1597
01:44:14,305 --> 01:44:16,265
I love her work.

1598
01:44:16,349 --> 01:44:18,643
I don't understand.

1599
01:44:18,726 --> 01:44:20,353
Jo-Ann is devastated.

1600
01:44:20,436 --> 01:44:23,064
She was at an exhibition.

1601
01:44:23,147 --> 01:44:24,982
She can't go back to the hotel.

1602
01:44:25,066 --> 01:44:27,318
The paparazzi have surrounded the place.

1603
01:44:28,361 --> 01:44:31,072
I suggested she join us. You don't mind?

1604
01:44:31,155 --> 01:44:33,074
No, of course not.

1605
01:44:46,087 --> 01:44:48,506
(turn signal clicking)

1606
01:45:05,481 --> 01:45:09,318
It was still just a rumor,
but the press knew something was up.

1607
01:45:09,402 --> 01:45:12,154
Someone posted in her blog
that it was the real reason

1608
01:45:12,238 --> 01:45:14,740
that Jo-Ann had accepted
to do a play in London.

1609
01:45:14,824 --> 01:45:16,325
And is that true?

1610
01:45:16,409 --> 01:45:20,663
She doesn't need a pretext to act in London,
but the paparazzi will never let go.

1611
01:45:20,746 --> 01:45:23,958
They need a picture with Christopher.
They're going wild.

1612
01:45:26,836 --> 01:45:28,337
(phone buzzes)

1613
01:45:29,422 --> 01:45:31,882
She's in her car.
She'll be here in five minutes.

1614
01:45:35,720 --> 01:45:38,889
- You wanted to talk to me?
- Sorry. I'm confused.

1615
01:45:40,599 --> 01:45:43,102
I had a long conversation
with Rosa last night.

1616
01:45:43,185 --> 01:45:47,898
I told her you were in London,
that we were about to start rehearsals.

1617
01:45:47,982 --> 01:45:49,525
That made her happy, I think.

1618
01:45:49,608 --> 01:45:52,945
Now all we have to do
is not disappoint her.

1619
01:45:55,614 --> 01:45:58,200
- Um, let's take Chateau Larousse.
- Thank you.

1620
01:45:59,118 --> 01:46:03,205
Rosa gave me fragments
from Wilhelm's follow-up to Maloja <i>Snake.</i>

1621
01:46:03,289 --> 01:46:05,332
A sign of her trust.

1622
01:46:05,416 --> 01:46:08,210
Some of the pages
make no sense out of context,

1623
01:46:08,294 --> 01:46:11,714
but there are a few others
that put the play in a new light.

1624
01:46:12,339 --> 01:46:14,884
How old was Wilhelm
when he wrote Maloja <i>Snake?</i>

1625
01:46:14,967 --> 01:46:17,011
Thirty-five or so? How -

1626
01:46:17,094 --> 01:46:18,554
Hmm. Thirty-eight.

1627
01:46:18,637 --> 01:46:20,139
- Thirty-eight?
- Yeah.

1628
01:46:20,222 --> 01:46:24,351
- Little older when he made the film.
- He was still a young man. All action.

1629
01:46:25,352 --> 01:46:28,064
Twenty-five years later,
obviously he was more analytical,

1630
01:46:28,147 --> 01:46:31,525
trying to put things in perspective,
maybe thinking about posterity.

1631
01:46:31,609 --> 01:46:33,569
Who knows?

1632
01:46:33,652 --> 01:46:36,697
Isn't it better to stay faithful
to his youthful energy?

1633
01:46:36,781 --> 01:46:38,491
- And forget the new scenes?
- Yes.

1634
01:46:41,160 --> 01:46:43,537
Wilhelm never had
any distance or maturity.

1635
01:46:43,621 --> 01:46:49,293
On the contrary, his last texts got bolder
and bolder and more and more enigmatic.

1636
01:46:50,795 --> 01:46:53,422
Here's another way of looking at it.

1637
01:46:53,506 --> 01:46:55,299
We think like him.

1638
01:46:55,382 --> 01:46:58,302
We - We project ourselves
into the future

1639
01:46:58,385 --> 01:47:01,680
instead of freezing ourselves
in the past so that we -

1640
01:47:01,764 --> 01:47:03,808
- Jo-Ann.
- Hi.

1641
01:47:04,642 --> 01:47:07,436
- What's happening?
- She's hanging on by a thread.

1642
01:47:07,520 --> 01:47:10,773
She's lost a lot of blood,
but the doctors won't tell us anything.

1643
01:47:10,856 --> 01:47:13,692
I mean, Chris said she was
really relaxed when he told her.

1644
01:47:13,776 --> 01:47:15,945
She was just getting used to
the new situation.

1645
01:47:16,028 --> 01:47:17,488
Where's Christopher?

1646
01:47:17,571 --> 01:47:19,824
Dorothea's family got home
from Germany, so he...

1647
01:47:19,907 --> 01:47:23,119
They told him to leave the hospital,
so he's going to come join us.

1648
01:47:23,202 --> 01:47:24,954
Here? But that's ridiculous.

1649
01:47:25,037 --> 01:47:27,957
He will have all the paparazzi
from the hospital on his trail.

1650
01:47:28,040 --> 01:47:30,459
No. He said there were no paparazzi.
He'd know.

1651
01:47:30,543 --> 01:47:32,795
He's being naive.
Of course they're tailing him.

1652
01:47:32,878 --> 01:47:37,049
They're just doing it discreetly.
Tell him absolutely not to join us.

1653
01:47:42,471 --> 01:47:45,724
His - His voice mail's turned off.
<i>I'll</i> just text him.

1654
01:47:46,767 --> 01:47:48,811
If they follow him here, we are stuck.

1655
01:47:49,770 --> 01:47:52,565
- Do you have your driver?
- Yeah. He's outside.

1656
01:47:53,566 --> 01:47:56,026
Okay. Tell Christopher
to meet us at my club.

1657
01:47:56,110 --> 01:47:58,445
At least we'll have
some peace and quiet.

1658
01:47:58,529 --> 01:48:00,156
- Here's the address.
- Chris!

1659
01:48:00,239 --> 01:48:02,074
Hey, hey-

1660
01:48:02,158 --> 01:48:03,993
Are you all right?

1661
01:48:04,076 --> 01:48:06,662
- Did you get my messages?
- Um -

1662
01:48:06,745 --> 01:48:10,583
Klaus thinks the paparazzi
are following you from the hospital.

1663
01:48:10,666 --> 01:48:13,043
I don't know. I... I didn't see any.

1664
01:48:13,127 --> 01:48:16,297
They can't get a picture of us tonight.
It'd be a total disaster.

1665
01:48:16,380 --> 01:48:19,466
It'd spread like wildfire.
I'm going to call my driver.

1666
01:48:21,719 --> 01:48:24,013
Hey. Will you come pick us up?

1667
01:48:24,096 --> 01:48:26,515
- All right.
- Here.

1668
01:48:26,599 --> 01:48:28,517
The address of my club.

1669
01:48:28,601 --> 01:48:31,562
<i>We'll</i> go first.
Wait five minutes, take a taxi and join us.

1670
01:48:44,700 --> 01:48:46,619
(engine starts)

1671
01:48:47,953 --> 01:48:49,455
(tires screech)

1672
01:48:59,256 --> 01:49:01,383
- Fuck, they're following us.
-(phone chiming)

1673
01:49:02,927 --> 01:49:04,386
Hey, Ari?

1674
01:49:04,470 --> 01:49:06,805
No, there's no news here
from the hospital.

1675
01:49:06,889 --> 01:49:10,059
Yeah, I could really use you right now.

1676
01:49:10,142 --> 01:49:11,894
Whatever the first plane out is.

1677
01:49:11,977 --> 01:49:15,189
I'm stuck here in London
till the end of the year.

1678
01:49:15,272 --> 01:49:17,358
Rehearsals start tomorrow.

1679
01:49:17,441 --> 01:49:19,526
If she doesn't make it,

1680
01:49:19,610 --> 01:49:22,571
it's going to be a nuclear fucking winter.

1681
01:49:22,655 --> 01:49:24,907
KLAUS: What do you want to do?
Change hotels?

1682
01:49:25,658 --> 01:49:29,495
No way. Wherever I go, they're just
gonna find me and chase me down.

1683
01:49:29,578 --> 01:49:31,497
I'd rather just stay where I am.

1684
01:49:31,580 --> 01:49:34,083
You know, it's... I'm fine with it.

1685
01:49:34,166 --> 01:49:36,168
It'll just be hard for Chris.

1686
01:49:36,252 --> 01:49:38,671
- The media is going to crucify him.
- No,no.

1687
01:49:38,754 --> 01:49:42,174
I'll take the heat.
I'll be the home wrecker.

1688
01:49:42,258 --> 01:49:45,594
I'm used to getting nasty shit written about me.
I could honestly care less.

1689
01:49:45,678 --> 01:49:49,098
You want us to cancel tomorrow's rehearsal?
Maria, would you mind?

1690
01:49:49,181 --> 01:49:51,725
- No, of course not, no.
- No way.

1691
01:49:51,809 --> 01:49:54,603
No, no, no. I'd rather work.

1692
01:49:59,525 --> 01:50:02,278
- We didn't get to talk much.
- No.

1693
01:50:02,361 --> 01:50:05,572
<i>I'll</i> have the new scenes dropped off
at the front desk.

1694
01:50:05,656 --> 01:50:07,783
And we'll talk about them seriously.

1695
01:50:07,866 --> 01:50:10,786
Yeah, we can do that tomorrow,
after rehearsal.

1696
01:50:10,869 --> 01:50:14,623
Mmm, I'm drained after a workday.
It's not the best time for me.

1697
01:50:14,707 --> 01:50:17,084
I know. Same for me.

1698
01:50:17,167 --> 01:50:21,297
And next weekend I have to
see my kids in southern Italy.

1699
01:50:22,715 --> 01:50:25,467
<i>We'll</i> manage. Okay, good night.

1700
01:50:25,551 --> 01:50:27,011
Good night.

1701
01:50:27,094 --> 01:50:29,638
(door opens, closes)

1702
01:50:36,562 --> 01:50:39,606
“When they tell me about you,
how much they appreciate you,

1703
01:50:39,690 --> 01:50:42,443
it's to remind me how happy they are

1704
01:50:42,526 --> 01:50:45,112
to grant you what they never granted me.

1705
01:50:46,113 --> 01:50:48,115
- They're using you -”
-(knocking)

1706
01:51:00,085 --> 01:51:02,129
- Hi.
- I printed everything out.

1707
01:51:02,212 --> 01:51:03,172
Thanks.

1708
01:51:03,255 --> 01:51:06,592
If you want an English solicitor
to take a look at the papers, tell me.

1709
01:51:06,675 --> 01:51:09,470
I know a bilingual girl
who specializes in Paris real estates.

1710
01:51:11,597 --> 01:51:13,015
That's the sales agreements.

1711
01:51:13,098 --> 01:51:16,685
Your ex-husband is buying your half
of the apartment for the price you agreed to.

1712
01:51:16,769 --> 01:51:19,772
No, I didn't want to discuss it.
Maybe I was wrong.

1713
01:51:20,522 --> 01:51:23,400
That's the sales agreement
for the studio on rue du Chemin Vert.

1714
01:51:23,484 --> 01:51:26,695
Yeah. it's expensive, but it's worth it.

1715
01:51:26,779 --> 01:51:29,114
- So it's ready to sign?
- Tomorrow, as planned.

1716
01:51:29,198 --> 01:51:32,409
You take the Eurostar at 8:15,
leave Paris at 5:00,

1717
01:51:32,493 --> 01:51:35,037
and you'll be back in London
in time for dinner.

1718
01:51:35,120 --> 01:51:37,206
- Okay.
- If you want, I can travel with you.

1719
01:51:37,289 --> 01:51:38,957
<i>No, I'm fine.</i>

1720
01:51:43,003 --> 01:51:44,963
WOMAN: What do I tell Piers Roaldson?

1721
01:51:45,047 --> 01:51:47,216
Remind me who he is.

1722
01:51:47,299 --> 01:51:51,804
He's shooting a film next summer
called <i>Electric Shockwave.</i>

1723
01:51:51,887 --> 01:51:53,514
What's he done?

1724
01:51:53,597 --> 01:51:55,307
Nothing. He's 25.

1725
01:51:55,391 --> 01:51:58,769
But Jay says it's good
and that it's been green-lit.

1726
01:51:58,852 --> 01:52:02,439
- What's the part?
- They haven't sent it over yet.

1727
01:52:02,523 --> 01:52:04,024
It's the lead.

1728
01:52:04,108 --> 01:52:07,319
I think your character would be
some sort of... hybrid.

1729
01:52:08,821 --> 01:52:12,074
Mm, a creation of modern genetics,
but with a soul.

1730
01:52:12,157 --> 01:52:15,327
It's set in the near future,
the 23rd century.

1731
01:52:15,411 --> 01:52:17,413
On Earth?

1732
01:52:17,496 --> 01:52:19,832
Maybe. I'm not sure.

1733
01:52:19,915 --> 01:52:21,500
(knocking)

1734
01:52:21,583 --> 01:52:25,129
Hello. Over there, please.

1735
01:52:26,004 --> 01:52:27,589
Thank you.

1736
01:52:27,673 --> 01:52:30,884
Well, tell Piers I'm interested,
and I'll read the script next week.

1737
01:52:30,968 --> 01:52:32,636
Okay?

1738
01:52:32,719 --> 01:52:35,139
And, uh, there are the new scenes
Klaus sent you.

1739
01:52:35,222 --> 01:52:37,558
- Ah, yes, I forgot.
- You want to run the lines?

1740
01:52:38,559 --> 01:52:40,978
No. I haven't read the pages yet.

1741
01:52:41,061 --> 01:52:42,813
He wants to know what you think.

1742
01:52:42,896 --> 01:52:45,107
Why doesn't he just call me?

1743
01:52:45,190 --> 01:52:47,359
Maybe he's waiting for your reaction.

1744
01:52:47,443 --> 01:52:49,653
You've had the scenes for two weeks.

1745
01:52:49,736 --> 01:52:51,697
I understand.

1746
01:52:51,780 --> 01:52:54,658
But I'd rather discover them
at the last minute and not overthink it.

1747
01:52:54,741 --> 01:52:58,454
It's the only way
I can keep it spontaneous.

1748
01:52:58,537 --> 01:53:01,540
That's how I, um, prepared Sigrid
20 years ago.

1749
01:53:01,623 --> 01:53:03,709
I'll do the same thing with Helena.

1750
01:53:04,751 --> 01:53:08,255
If he asks you, just tell him
I think they're very good.

1751
01:53:09,173 --> 01:53:12,676
♪♪ (orchestra: classical)

1752
01:54:01,350 --> 01:54:03,018
(files hit floor)

1753
01:54:07,564 --> 01:54:09,942
KLAUS:
Very good, but it's still a little long.

1754
01:54:10,776 --> 01:54:13,403
- Jo-Ann, can you hear me?
- Uh,yeah.

1755
01:54:13,487 --> 01:54:16,365
- Do the same thing, but speed it up a little.
- Okay.

1756
01:54:16,448 --> 01:54:19,409
Why don't you just forget one of the files?
There are plenty.

1757
01:54:19,493 --> 01:54:21,745
- We do it one more time.
- Okay.

1758
01:54:25,374 --> 01:54:27,084
Excuse me.

1759
01:54:27,167 --> 01:54:29,711
- Tomorrow is our final dress rehearsal.
- I know.

1760
01:54:29,795 --> 01:54:32,214
- Thanks for taking the time.
- My pleasure.

1761
01:54:32,297 --> 01:54:34,758
<i>I'll</i> just switch this on.

1762
01:54:34,841 --> 01:54:37,761
Uh, may I have a cup of coffee, please?

1763
01:54:37,844 --> 01:54:40,138
You can imagine my first question.

1764
01:54:40,222 --> 01:54:45,185
Will the media frenzy around Jo-Ann Ellis
steal the spotlight?

1765
01:54:45,269 --> 01:54:48,355
All that matters is the show.
The rest is of no importance.

1766
01:54:48,438 --> 01:54:51,567
And fortunately, Dorothea pulled through.

1767
01:54:51,650 --> 01:54:55,404
I know you have a new take on it,
but will the audience be receptive

1768
01:54:55,487 --> 01:54:57,406
or might they be too distracted?

1769
01:54:57,489 --> 01:54:59,324
I suppose that's my question.

1770
01:54:59,408 --> 01:55:01,285
I hope they'll be receptive.

1771
01:55:01,368 --> 01:55:03,412
So you think the shows are airtight?

1772
01:55:03,495 --> 01:55:06,331
No connection to the outside world.

1773
01:55:06,415 --> 01:55:07,708
No.

1774
01:55:07,791 --> 01:55:10,794
No, each theatergoer
brings his own subjectivity.

1775
01:55:10,877 --> 01:55:14,339
And it's generally not defined
by tabloid headlines.

1776
01:55:14,423 --> 01:55:16,508
Some will go for the smell of scandal.

1777
01:55:16,592 --> 01:55:19,970
So will they see the show you had in mind,
or something else?

1778
01:55:22,472 --> 01:55:24,600
- MARIA: Jo-Ann?
- What's up?

1779
01:55:24,683 --> 01:55:26,476
I wanted to ask you -

1780
01:55:26,560 --> 01:55:29,313
You know the scene
at the beginning of act 3

1781
01:55:29,396 --> 01:55:33,609
when you tell me you want to leave
and I get on my knees and beg you to stay?

1782
01:55:33,692 --> 01:55:37,404
You're on the phone ordering pepperoncino
pizza for your coworkers in Accounting.

1783
01:55:37,487 --> 01:55:40,699
Well, you... you leave
without looking at me,

1784
01:55:40,782 --> 01:55:43,452
as if I didn't exist.

1785
01:55:43,535 --> 01:55:45,621
Um...

1786
01:55:45,704 --> 01:55:47,914
if you could pause for a second,
you know,

1787
01:55:47,998 --> 01:55:52,836
Helena's distress would last longer
when she's left alone in her office.

1788
01:55:54,087 --> 01:55:56,965
Well, the way you're playing it, um,

1789
01:55:57,049 --> 01:56:00,636
the audience follows you out,
but instantly forgets about her, so...

1790
01:56:01,470 --> 01:56:04,806
So... So what?

1791
01:56:04,890 --> 01:56:08,268
Well, when I played Sigrid,
I... I held it longer.

1792
01:56:08,352 --> 01:56:11,563
I thought it was more powerful,
dramatically.

1793
01:56:11,647 --> 01:56:13,523
I mean, it really played well.

1794
01:56:13,607 --> 01:56:17,319
Well, no one really gives a fuck
about Helena at that point, do they?

1795
01:56:17,402 --> 01:56:21,198
I'm sorry, but I mean, it's pretty clear to me
this poor woman's all washed up.

1796
01:56:21,281 --> 01:56:23,825
I mean, your character, right? Not you.

1797
01:56:23,909 --> 01:56:27,829
And... when Sigrid leaves Helena's office,

1798
01:56:27,913 --> 01:56:29,998
Helena is a wreck, and we get it.

1799
01:56:30,082 --> 01:56:32,334
You know, it's time to move on.

1800
01:56:32,417 --> 01:56:34,711
I think they want what comes next.

1801
01:56:35,504 --> 01:56:38,423
If you just held it a few seconds longer.

1802
01:56:38,507 --> 01:56:41,510
It doesn't really feel right for me, Maria.

1803
01:56:41,593 --> 01:56:43,095
(forced chuckle)

1804
01:56:44,012 --> 01:56:45,597
You're right.

1805
01:56:46,682 --> 01:56:48,642
Yeah.

1806
01:56:48,725 --> 01:56:50,227
I, um...

1807
01:56:51,603 --> 01:56:55,107
I think I'm lost in my memories.

1808
01:56:55,190 --> 01:56:57,651
You think you've forgotten
your old habits,

1809
01:56:57,734 --> 01:56:59,528
but they all - they all come back.

1810
01:56:59,611 --> 01:57:01,905
I have to break them.

1811
01:57:01,988 --> 01:57:04,449
I guess you do.
(chuckles)

1812
01:57:18,797 --> 01:57:21,466
Excuse me.
I'm looking for Maria Enders' room.

1813
01:57:21,550 --> 01:57:23,802
-(bell ringing)
-(woman, indistinct)

1814
01:57:23,885 --> 01:57:25,387
Thank you.

1815
01:57:29,433 --> 01:57:31,435
- Hi. Come in.
- Hi.

1816
01:57:32,352 --> 01:57:35,480
Thanks so much for seeing me tonight.
I really appreciate it.

1817
01:57:35,564 --> 01:57:38,942
We're leaving early tomorrow morning
for a location scout in the Ukraine.

1818
01:57:39,651 --> 01:57:41,820
That's where we're gonna
be shooting our exteriors, mostly.

1819
01:57:41,903 --> 01:57:44,156
So, I - I read your script.

1820
01:57:44,239 --> 01:57:48,410
Yeah, well, um, I know we've never met,
but I actually wrote it with you in mind.

1821
01:57:48,493 --> 01:57:50,620
(sighs)
As a mutant?

1822
01:57:50,704 --> 01:57:54,666
I'm trying to consider genetics
from a more human point of view.

1823
01:57:56,126 --> 01:58:00,547
When I was reading it, um,
I imagined someone much younger.

1824
01:58:00,630 --> 01:58:02,799
Maybe me younger, actually,

1825
01:58:02,883 --> 01:58:06,094
but you're seeing me in movies
that were made years ago.

1826
01:58:06,178 --> 01:58:07,679
I've changed.

1827
01:58:07,763 --> 01:58:09,681
She has no age.

1828
01:58:09,765 --> 01:58:13,769
Or else she's every age at once,
like all of us.

1829
01:58:14,978 --> 01:58:16,855
Can I be frank?

1830
01:58:18,356 --> 01:58:21,985
Maybe it's because I'm working with her,
but... as I was reading it,

1831
01:58:22,068 --> 01:58:25,113
I kept thinking about Jo-Ann.

1832
01:58:25,197 --> 01:58:28,200
Yeah, well, personally,

1833
01:58:28,283 --> 01:58:30,952
I never think about Jo-Ann Ellis.

1834
01:58:31,036 --> 01:58:34,331
You're wrong.
She's smart... and talented.

1835
01:58:34,414 --> 01:58:37,042
She's modern, just like your character.

1836
01:58:37,125 --> 01:58:40,462
My character isn't modern.
Not in that way, anyway.

1837
01:58:40,545 --> 01:58:43,006
She's... outside of time.

1838
01:58:43,089 --> 01:58:45,050
Outside of time.

1839
01:58:48,261 --> 01:58:50,972
I don't understand.
It's too abstract for me.

1840
01:58:51,056 --> 01:58:52,516
(chuckling)
Sorry.

1841
01:58:52,599 --> 01:58:55,644
I, uh - I don't like this era.

1842
01:58:55,727 --> 01:58:57,395
You're wrong. it's yours.

1843
01:58:57,479 --> 01:58:59,231
Hey, man, I didn't choose it.

1844
01:59:00,398 --> 01:59:03,860
And if my era is Jo-Ann Ellis
and viral Internet scandals,

1845
01:59:03,944 --> 01:59:06,571
I think I'm entitled
to feel unrelated, aren't I?

1846
01:59:07,989 --> 01:59:11,576
I mean, it's nothing against her.
I guessed I just assumed you'd understand.

1847
01:59:12,619 --> 01:59:14,162
(knocking)

1848
01:59:14,246 --> 01:59:15,831
Curtain in five minutes.

1849
01:59:15,914 --> 01:59:18,083
- How's the house?
- Full.

1850
01:59:19,125 --> 01:59:21,127
♪♪ (orchestra: classical)

1851
01:59:26,675 --> 01:59:29,177
Take your cue, please.

